{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/posts/10.30.20/Working_with_gatsby/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>The react and node based <a href=\"http://www.gatsbyjs.com\">Gatsby</a> takes a lot of the pain and configuration away from utilizing react and react-router to create and generate multi-page 'static' websites. (In fact, the newest version of Gatsby makes use of reach-router- a router that borrows from several react-router style components)</p>\n<p>Because Gatsby is based on React components, sites could even generate some content dynamically, say, by using an external API.</p>\n<p>The real appeal to me, currently, is the abilty to parse markdown files into self-contained pages 'semi-dynamically'(at build time). This is great for something like this website, as I expect content updates to be relatively infrequent, but appreciate the scalability and easy of use of simply, putting a markdown file in the correct location and running <code>gatsby build</code>.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 559px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 16%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAADCAIAAAAcOLh5AAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAfElEQVQI1y2Oaw6DQAiEPUg1vAbch8lq+7f3v1ZZK4EEhskHi0ZjRIU0WIHtps1R3dZ1fd35xPbUVLbtry9+fb2PcZ3vzzmOUkwTUWEm7Cahko0JKZMKQwQqQuTKwrSgHIydopNYWsu8r7kL0x7oPn+5lQlqgeQmpUJz/AHxLxlYspPcAAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg=='); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post*' title='*markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post*' src='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/8a4e8/frontmatter.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/5a46d/frontmatter.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/6f2f28398bd329e5fbd1c58e846dcfd6/a65ce/frontmatter.png 559w' sizes='(max-width: 559px) 100vw, 559px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>markdown frontmatter is programatically read to create this post</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>There have been plenty of resources to aid in configuring this setup, though I will say working with Gatsby's data api is daunting.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 595px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 36.66666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical*' title='*setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical*' src='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/8a4e8/createnode.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/5a46d/createnode.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/9dcd0a2965d5ca5427796a880f138cdb/3dd3e/createnode.png 595w' sizes='(max-width: 595px) 100vw, 595px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>setting up programatic page generation isnt intuitive, but is logical</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>I found the <a href=\"https://gatsbyjs.com/tutorial/part-four\">data in gatsby</a> tutorial particularly helpful.</p>\n<p><figure class='gatsby-resp-image-figure' style=''>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-wrapper' style='position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 489px; '>\n      <a class='gatsby-resp-image-link' href='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png' style='display: block' target='_blank' rel='noopener'>\n    <span class='gatsby-resp-image-background-image' style=\"padding-bottom: 62.66666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class='gatsby-resp-image-image' alt='*gatsby utilizes Graphql queries*' title='*gatsby utilizes Graphql queries*' src='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png' srcset='/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/8a4e8/graphql.png 150w,\n/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/5a46d/graphql.png 300w,\n/tknapp/static/cb79a72a62429254de3ec415550b5d10/03e1f/graphql.png 489w' sizes='(max-width: 489px) 100vw, 489px' style='width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;' loading='lazy'>\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class='gatsby-resp-image-figcaption'><p><em>gatsby utilizes Graphql queries</em></p></figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Gatsby works with its own GraphQL system, something with which I have very little familiarity- though the query language looks extremely flexible. I'm looking forward to learning more about GraphQL, maybe through the <a href=\"https://fullstackopen.com/en/\">Full Stack Open</a> course- which I have been curious about exploring for a while.</p>\n<p>Building this website has (so far) felt fairly intuitive- I'm really looking forward to learning more about gatsby, and adding it to my tool-belt.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Working with Gatsby","description":"Learning to use a new framework built on the power of react.","date":"10/30/20","location":"posts"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/10.30.20/Working_with_gatsby/"}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}